China Stocks: Chitianhua, Huadian Power, Shandong Dacheng

-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 
2011-03-31T08:29:16Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-30/bank-of-communications-baoshan-icbc-china-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in China trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses as of 3 p.m. close.  The Shanghai Composite Index, which tracks the bigger of
China’s stock exchanges, fell 27.66, or 0.9 percent, to
2,928.11. The  CSI 300 Index (SHSZ300)  declined 1 percent to 3,223.29.  Nuclear power equipment makers: Dongfang Electric Corp.
(600875 CH), which derived 6.5 percent of its revenue from
nuclear power-related products in 2009, dropped 1.6 percent to
27.22 yuan. Shanghai Electric Group Co. (601727 CH) slipped 1
percent to 7.79 yuan.  China will reduce its 2020 nuclear capacity goal of 80
gigawatts, Ren Dongmin, the head of the renewable energy
development of the National Development and Reform Commission,
said at a Beijing conference today, without giving a new target.  Guizhou Chitianhua Co. (600227 CH), a fertilizer maker,
slid 9.9 percent to 6.99 yuan, the biggest decline since
November 2008. The company said in a statement yesterday its
Huaizi coal mine isn’t rich in rare earth in clarification to
speculation circulating on the Internet.  Huadian Power International Corp. (600027 CH), the listed
unit of  China ’s fourth-largest electricity producer, dropped 3.5
percent to 3.61 yuan after saying net income fell 82 percent to
208 million yuan ($31.7 million) last year by Chinese accounting
standards.  Shandong Dacheng Pesticide Co. (600882 CH), a manufacturer
of pesticides, jumped by the 10 percent daily limit to 10.12
yuan as the stock resumed trading today after being suspended
more than two months. The company plans to have mining assets
worth 1.9 billion yuan injected in an asset swap with
affiliates, Dacheng said in a statement yesterday.  --Zhang Shidong. Editor: Richard Frost  To contact Bloomberg News staff for this story:
